00:34:10.250 --> 00:34:14.830
I actually physically know who
is-- but I think-- but I'm also

00:34:14.830 --> 00:34:17.580
thinking, who is that person?

00:34:17.580 --> 00:34:19.420
What are they going through?

00:34:19.420 --> 00:34:20.679
What--

00:34:20.679 --> 00:34:24.780
Instead of my judgments,
what a jerk, what,

00:34:24.780 --> 00:34:27.420
who, how could they say this?

00:34:27.420 --> 00:34:29.400
It's changed the way I think.

00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:30.750
I don't like it.

00:34:30.750 --> 00:34:31.980
But I feel pain.

00:34:31.980 --> 00:34:33.060
I feel sad.

00:34:33.060 --> 00:34:42.760
But I-- technology, it
can bring people closer.

00:34:42.760 --> 00:34:45.070
It can-- it's a way to
stay in touch with people.

00:34:45.070 --> 00:34:50.020
And just a quick note,
caring, thinking about you,

00:34:50.020 --> 00:34:51.219
how's your day?

00:34:51.219 --> 00:34:55.540
Something like that can
pick you up, make your day.

00:34:55.540 --> 00:34:59.650
And instead of maybe
statements and judgments,

00:34:59.650 --> 00:35:01.270
what do you think about this?

00:35:04.280 --> 00:35:07.880
A lot on people's
minds are politics.

00:35:07.880 --> 00:35:13.830
And because I've
learned not to judge,

00:35:13.830 --> 00:35:16.980
and I still judge when
I see things going on

00:35:16.980 --> 00:35:18.880
in the political world.

00:35:18.880 --> 00:35:21.030
But I'm not making
that person wrong

00:35:21.030 --> 00:35:24.460
because I don't know what
their childhood was like.

00:35:24.460 --> 00:35:28.620
I don't know what their
brain chemistry is like.

00:35:28.620 --> 00:35:32.790
I know their strategy to meet
their need for acceptance,

00:35:32.790 --> 00:35:39.630
appreciation, community,
included a strategy to say,

00:35:39.630 --> 00:35:40.528
we like these people.

00:35:40.528 --> 00:35:41.820
But we don't like those people.

00:35:41.820 --> 00:35:45.240
So, and that I feel sad.

00:35:45.240 --> 00:35:46.920
HENRY FAULKNER: This
is interesting is

00:35:46.920 --> 00:35:49.060
I think when we
talk about empathy,

00:35:49.060 --> 00:35:51.700
I'm thinking about
this other person

00:35:51.700 --> 00:35:53.640
and how can I think about them.

00:35:53.640 --> 00:35:56.820
But when you describe
like, oh, try

00:35:56.820 --> 00:36:00.000
to-- when you're
reading trolling reviews

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:03.960
and having some empathy
for the person there,

00:36:03.960 --> 00:36:05.970
that seems like that's for me.

00:36:05.970 --> 00:36:07.620
That's something,
that almost seems

00:36:07.620 --> 00:36:09.431
like empathy is self-defense.

00:36:12.139 --> 00:36:13.222
MICHAEL JASCZ: I hear you.

00:36:13.222 --> 00:36:15.150
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:18.050 --> 00:36:20.470
I wouldn't say I have--

00:36:20.470 --> 00:36:22.280
that empathy comes up for me.

00:36:22.280 --> 00:36:28.130
It's more what do I feel,
my feeling, and noticing

00:36:28.130 --> 00:36:32.270
that I'm just not judging.

00:36:32.270 --> 00:36:34.730
Mary Louise is our office
manager sitting here.

00:36:34.730 --> 00:36:39.770
Corinne is our intern
from Dartmouth University.

00:36:39.770 --> 00:36:45.055
Have you heard me say any
judgment words about anyone?

00:36:45.055 --> 00:36:46.840
AUDIENCE: Never.

00:36:46.840 --> 00:36:49.130
MICHAEL JASCZ: Except
myself maybe, right?

00:36:49.130 --> 00:36:54.340
Because it brings
the atmosphere down.

00:36:54.340 --> 00:36:56.290
I don't know what's
wrong with somebody.

00:36:56.290 --> 00:37:00.170
I'm just wondering what
their unmet needs are.

00:37:00.170 --> 00:37:01.730
What are our unmet needs.

00:37:01.730 --> 00:37:05.560
And I just also want to mention
while people are still here,

00:37:05.560 --> 00:37:09.520
in New York, there's
an amazing organization

00:37:09.520 --> 00:37:12.820
called New York Center for
nonviolent communication.

00:37:12.820 --> 00:37:15.160
NYCNVC.

00:37:15.160 --> 00:37:16.310
And they have monthly--

00:37:16.310 --> 00:37:18.400
the first Monday
of the month, they

00:37:18.400 --> 00:37:23.080
have a bi donation, whatever you
can spare for an introduction

00:37:23.080 --> 00:37:24.520
to NVC.

00:37:24.520 --> 00:37:29.320
NYCNVC is-- that's where I've
learned most of what I know

00:37:29.320 --> 00:37:32.590
about nonviolent communication.

00:37:32.590 --> 00:37:34.660
And we don't-- this
word nonviolent.

00:37:34.660 --> 00:37:36.760
We don't think of ourself
as violent people.

00:37:36.760 --> 00:37:40.240
We associate it with wars
and beatings and killings.

00:37:40.240 --> 00:37:44.200
But are some of the words
we say hurtful and have

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:48.760
a lot of hurtful words between
countries led to violence?

00:37:48.760 --> 00:37:50.430
Hey, your country stinks.

00:37:50.430 --> 00:37:52.060
Hey, your country stinks, too.

00:37:52.060 --> 00:37:54.828
All right, let's go to war.

00:37:54.828 --> 00:37:55.870
We can do it differently.

00:37:55.870 --> 00:37:57.453
I think that's usually
how it happens.

00:37:57.453 --> 00:37:58.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:37:58.980 --> 00:38:01.150
HENRY FAULKNER: All right,
so one last question

00:38:01.150 --> 00:38:04.605
is that, I mean, obviously,
there's graduation rates

00:38:04.605 --> 00:38:05.480
and things like this.

00:38:05.480 --> 00:38:09.520
But in terms of just applying
this in our relationships,

00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:12.080
how are we going to
know we got this right?

00:38:12.080 --> 00:38:13.340
Like what's the metric.

00:38:13.340 --> 00:38:15.090
What should we be looking at?

00:38:15.090 --> 00:38:18.100
We're all-- there's a lot
of data scientist here.

00:38:18.100 --> 00:38:21.900
We like numbers.

00:38:21.900 --> 00:38:26.140
MICHAEL JASCZ: OK, I only
have one number for you

00:38:26.140 --> 00:38:27.793
at the moment.

00:38:27.793 --> 00:38:29.210
My friend Marissa's
in the office.

00:38:29.210 --> 00:38:31.650
She's a relationship
extraordinaire.

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:33.770
We've coached couples together.

00:38:33.770 --> 00:38:36.580
And one of the very
first things that

00:38:36.580 --> 00:38:40.120
as couples when we meet
couples, they're blaming,

00:38:40.120 --> 00:38:42.550
shaming, right,
wrong, should, should.

00:38:42.550 --> 00:38:48.790
We have them practice
saying tell me more.

00:38:48.790 --> 00:38:49.690
I hear you.

00:38:49.690 --> 00:38:53.590
Not defending, not
criticizing back.

00:38:53.590 --> 00:38:54.550
I hear you.

00:38:54.550 --> 00:38:55.670
Tell me more.

00:38:55.670 --> 00:38:57.880
And we can see
the transformation

00:38:57.880 --> 00:39:00.330
in their faces and
their physiology.

00:39:00.330 --> 00:39:02.370
It's to add that
to your vocabulary.

00:39:02.370 --> 00:39:05.090
It doesn't mean you won't
criticize and defend,

00:39:05.090 --> 00:39:09.290
because that's been our
programming for a lot of--

00:39:09.290 --> 00:39:10.540
but simple words.

00:39:10.540 --> 00:39:12.580
I hear you.

00:39:12.580 --> 00:39:13.840
Is there more to that?

00:39:13.840 --> 00:39:14.780
Tell me more.

00:39:14.780 --> 00:39:15.950
And what are you feeling?

00:39:15.950 --> 00:39:17.760
What are you needing?

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:21.930
Do you need affection,
acceptance, appreciation?

00:39:21.930 --> 00:39:25.320
Are you feeling
like you need space.

00:39:25.320 --> 00:39:27.670
Let's meet up in 20
minutes because I

00:39:27.670 --> 00:39:30.280
had the toughest day at work.

00:39:30.280 --> 00:39:32.080
I need space.

00:39:32.080 --> 00:39:34.130
I need connection.

00:39:34.130 --> 00:39:38.260
That's the key word that I get
from nonviolent communication

00:39:38.260 --> 00:39:41.680
is connection, connection,
connection, connection, which

00:39:41.680 --> 00:39:45.900
seems to go on here,
a focus on connection

00:39:45.900 --> 00:39:48.420
because you're
connecting the world.

00:39:48.420 --> 00:39:50.230
And here you have
the opportunity

00:39:50.230 --> 00:39:52.620
to connect with each other.

00:39:52.620 --> 00:39:55.850
HENRY FAULKNER: Well, and on
that note, thank you very much,

00:39:55.850 --> 00:39:57.280
Michael, pleasure.

